          "body": "The parable of the pot (24:3–14) inverts an earlier boast. In Ezekiel 11:3, Jerusalem's remaining inhabitants had congratulated themselves: 'Is not the city the pot and we the flesh?' — meaning: we are the choice meat, safely enclosed by Jerusalem's walls. Ezekiel 24 seizes that metaphor and turns it into a death sentence. Yes, the pot contains good pieces, choice cuts, the thigh and shoulder — but the pot itself is rusted, its walls corroded with bloodguilt that no amount of cooking can dislodge (24:6). The escalation of the parable is deliberate: first cook the meat (24:3–5), then remove the pieces — not the best, not the worst, but randomly (24:6); then empty the pot and heat it until the bronze glows, until the very rust is consumed (24:10–11). Three stages of judgment: siege, deportation, total destruction. The theological climax is verse 13: God offered cleansing repeatedly — *I would have cleansed you* — but Jerusalem refused. The impurity is not merely historical; it is volitional. 'You will not be cleansed from your filthiness again until I have spent My wrath on you.' This is not divine impatience; it is the record of exhausted grace.'"
